WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Today is Monday, March 11, 2013. My name is John Dittmer and I'm here in Durant, Mississippi with videographer John Bishop to interview Mr. Walter Bruce, a leading civil rights activist in the Holmes County Movement.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
First of all, Mr. Bruce, we're delighted to be here today and thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:50.000
I'd like to begin by asking you about your home and family. Were you born and raised in Holmes County?

00:00:50.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Yes, I was in a little community called Rolling Wall out in the country. That's what I was born in. What did your parents do?

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.000
They got a little share of crop and just a little bit and I know what I'm doing.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
What was it like to be growing, were you on a plantation then?

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Not just a plantation, we don't know. Whitefoot had some land out there but we wouldn't like to deal with anything.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:30.000
If you want to have crops, you can do it. What was your start picking cotton?

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:38.000
I never picked my little cotton. I hope it's good but I can't remember no cotton.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:50.000
I bet you don't regret not being able to. When did you move to Durant at what point?

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:56.000
He was in the early 60s. You were back there in Rosewater?

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Rosewater. Tell us something about your childhood experiences. What you remember growing up in that area of the county?

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Growing up out there, being a teenager. A whole lot of people lived out in that community.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:34.000
I formed a little league, baseball team. I ran it for about 15 or 16 years. Then I started a gospel group and on into the civil right movement.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:40.000
I talked about the gospel group a little later. Where did you go to school?

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:46.000
I started off at the Roe Wall. When I finished out there, I went to Ambrose School in Latin.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Tell us something about your teachers and subjects.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:02.000
I was there. You got an 8th grade and then I moved in Latin. I had a sister in Latin.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:12.000
I finished 12th grade at Ambrose High School. Now they got to New School with my claim. At that time, Ambrole High School.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:18.000
It was rather unusual for people to finish high school, wasn't it?

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
So you liked studying?

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Yeah, I liked it.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
What do you remember about your teachers?

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Well, not in a whole lot. It's been a long time. I was teaching at the end of the day.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
We were quite different from then and now.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Did you have brothers and sisters?

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Yeah, I had 13 of them, six brothers and seven sisters. All of them had a way with me.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Oh, wow. Where were you on the list?

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
On the baby.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
You were the baby of the family.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
You probably had brothers and sisters as adults when you were growing up.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Oh, yes, you.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
And they had kids you played with. And you were their uncle.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Yeah, man.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Could we call this for a distance?

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:13.000
The problem?

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Okay, we're back.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Okay.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Just take up work.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Yeah, just take up work.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Okay. We were talking about school.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
What about church?

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Was church important in your family?

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Yeah, all my family was changed.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So Baptist?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Methodist.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Methodist. I see.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Tell us something about what you remember from church and the importance for your family.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Well, when I was at that road wall, we had a little wooden church.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.000
A couple of miles from where we stayed, but we used to walk over it.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
We had like two sons of a month.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:01.000
But we had to, I know, remember the creek right in between Iowa, Hoppe and the church.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
We always cut a tree and threw it.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Throw it down with some blanked up bay and roll.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
That's what we went to church.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
We had an animal call, anything like that.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Wow.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So your folks were supporting 13 kids.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Were they able to do that on cotton, on chair capping?

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Yeah.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
That must have been everybody pitching in.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Yeah.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
How many acres did your father...

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
We didn't own an acre.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
How large was the area you farmed?

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:34.000
We didn't.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.000
It wasn't all always for him.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Maybe like two or three acres of the farm.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:38.000
Oh really?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:39.000
Oh, I see.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.000
So it was...

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Yeah.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And did you fly behind the mule?

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Yes, I applied a little bit.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
I mean, one time when I was small, I wanted to fly this one.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And never done that.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Never did I pull it.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
You know, the moon was started.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
I had been asking my dad, he didn't let me fly.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:06.000
So the day that he said, I have to meet a fly.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.000
And then he told me that day that I won't be able to fly.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
I called it a star.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
He got out and there was a white put a deer on it.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:17.000
Bird was in there.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:18.000
Oh man.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Yes.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And he had...

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
And his star got out and when they went up by, he's out.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And put him in the foward, you know.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And when they were about to give him, he told me, you know, he had to pay $1 a year to get him.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And he told me, now, $1 a year.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:43.000
And so finally, he came back to the house and told me that he couldn't give him, because he didn't have no money.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
And so I finally got to drop on him.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And so, as he kind of disappeared, then I went up there by myself and knocked on the door.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And what he went with me, I said, I can't hear my little me.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
Did he tell you that you were going to have a dollar of peace?

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
I said, yeah, he told me that I didn't have no love.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And I said, well, I tell you what, I tell you you don't let him out, I'm gonna let him out of my self.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
And he said, it's all gone.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.000
And then the boy had a little me.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And boy, he got no sense.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
That's interesting.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So you stood up to him?

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:23.000
Yeah.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
Tell us something about race relations.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
How many whites were there in the area?

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
What were your other contacts?

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Well, white in the air was heavy, probably, you know, when the moon was starting.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
He was more white in the city.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:49.000
But the county, you know, most men told him black, but, you know, at that time, you couldn't tell him,

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
the white air control was heavy.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Yeah.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:58.000
One of the things we were talking about children today, not realizing about the old times.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And of course, one of the major factors of life back then was Jim Crow segregation.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:11.000
For these younger people, tell us what it was like to live in a segregated society.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Well, it was kind of rough, you know, but like I said, I guess, you know,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
at that time, you know, it wasn't too hard to get along with, but, you know,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
it wasn't too much you could do about it.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
But, you know, we kind of got along.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.000
As I said now, at all the time that I've been in the moon or even for them,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
I never hated white for right.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
It didn't like what they were waiting, you know, did it.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:44.000
But I needed hating them, you know, like that, like that.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
But whoever I had to say or do, I just, you know, going to do it.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Was there any, are any racial incidents, any violence or anything that you remember

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
around when you were growing up?

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:59.000
Well, that's about the only thing that I knew about, you know, is that I said,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:06.000
when the stock got out of there, well, we, we, you know, not too far apart, you know,

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:11.000
we kind of communicated together, but I never had no more problem after that happened.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.000
How old were you when you went up there?

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
Oh, about 27 or 8.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
Oh, no, getting.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
What a wonderful story.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Yeah.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Yeah.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
It was awesome that the second is coming in the role.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:30.000
What kind of law enforcement do you remember in police sheriff?

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
Were they visible presence?

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
Not too much.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:44.000
I mean, all at that time, you know, all safe from police problems, all white.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:52.000
But basically, is it safe to say that, that you had limited contact with white stirring

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
you're growing up years?

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
I didn't know I know a lot of problems I'd grown up.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
Most problems I had with them was in the early 60s.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Yeah, well, we're going to get to that soon.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Did you rephrase the question?

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:21.000
Well, I think that you were growing up and you had limited contacts with whites.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:25.000
Was it black community and you saved pretty much in the black community?

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.000
Did you work at all outside the home other than sharecropping?

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
Oh, yeah.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Well, I said, I was a common problem for my up, for my 16-year birth,

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:41.000
they own owned up to every time.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Well, I want you to talk about that.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Did you have the skills to be a carpenter?

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Did you apprentice yourself to someone or did you just pick it up?

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
No, I told some of them, I mean, that question, I told them,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
I never went to school to be a carp.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
And so, it was just a great gift from God.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:07.000
Then I started out calming and I don't know how I'm in a house.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:13.000
I was getting a house kind of a taller county, old 60, I spent.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Did you have a crew working with you?

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.000
I had two more friends working with me.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And who bought these?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
Who were you building these homes for?

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:27.000
I built some of white and brown.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
After I got you started in the civil right and moved,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.000
I mean, when I first started, I was thinking that I wasn't on white going high,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
and that's what I was thinking about when I got started in the civil right movement.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
But then I think the whole run of them,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:51.000
they were kind of friends, they didn't have them, maybe I would have.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
Do something against that bend.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.000
So you were a contractor when you were a teenager,

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
or did you just start hiring out to yourself?

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
When did you build your first house?

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
Do you remember that at all?

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:13.000
No, I know I can't really...

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
The first one I was...

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
I'm trying to think what you want to know.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
But are your houses still, are some of them still standing?

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.000
All of them.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
All of them are still standing.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:26.000
Yeah, everyone.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Wow.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So you can just drive around the county and you can see what you did.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:33.000
Yeah.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
That's amazing.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:38.000
Yeah, and you were a singer.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
How did you get to be a singer?

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
Well, just like you said, you're like,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
I'm an art and baseball team.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
All my life, that's almost I ever did a fool around with people.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
You know, from teenage, you don't want to add up.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:55.000
And then we started this group.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:00.000
And this page, October, we celebrated our 54-year-old good.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Wow.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
So tell us about what kind of songs...

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Who else was in the group, what kind of songs did you sing?

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.000
Where did you sing?

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:13.000
We sung, we sang all night, two homes, kind of,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Tallahowne, Leflore County, Counting, Waterloo Chicago.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Wow.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Me and Walker.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
So you were well known outside this thing?

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:25.000
Oh, sure.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And you did a lot of touring, did you?

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Yeah, we did a whole lot.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:30.000
You did.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
When were you most popular?

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
When was your group the most popular?

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Well, we still put it popular.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
But you did radio broadcasts?

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
We do radio broadcasts right now.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:42.000
It was fun.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Wow.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:44.000
What's the station?

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:45.000
W-H-T-N-L-E.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:46.000
Wow.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
You make any records?

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.000
Yeah.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Well, we make...

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Getting ready to make a number, we got...

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Going solo, just about...

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.000
I got some...

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
Maybe I have one, I know I got some tape, plenty of tapes in here.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
But those CDs, they go real fast.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.000
Yeah.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Are all the members of your original group still in it?

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
Or have you had replacements?

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
Well, we don't have the whole lot of them.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
The whole lot of them passed away.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Yeah.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.000
Most of them...

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
I'm the only one that's been in there for 50-something years.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
I've already read them since then.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:26.000
Because one of them then started out with me, all of them, and passed away.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Well, music was very important in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.000
Yes, it was.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
Talk a little bit about that.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:38.000
Why it was that there was so much music and what it did for people.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
Well, I think...

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:48.000
I say what the Black was going through, and they just got connected, you know, with the church and gospel songs,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and all like that.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And I sound like they like the blues, but most of the people that went to church all the time,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:59.000
they really liked that gospel singing.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.000
And then did you were the...

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
Was singing a major part of the mass meetings that you had?

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
Yeah, we always were proud of the song.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:15.000
We had all the kind of why I mean we call them.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Well, let's then turn to the Civil Rights Movement in Holmes County, and in Mississippi, and your role ended.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:32.000
What are your first recollections of the Civil Rights Movement underway?

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:40.000
Well, if I were, you know, growing up and seeing everything, you know, they were going on.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
And I was just going to...

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Yes, that's right after the first beginning", I wasn't as active as I was a little late on because,

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:59.000
as I said, by me being a contractor, you know, and I was wanting to know if I was taking the part in the Civil Rights Movement,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:05.000
you know, would I be able to get the jobs and find that I was getting?

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.000
I don't know, then something just kind of means that, well, what good is a job?

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
You ain't got no freedom.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:18.000
And so when I just went on and did what I had to do, and then things didn't go away, I just let them know who I felt about it.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:23.000
And so that's where I really got started.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So, I...

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:32.000
Do you remember, well, there were a number of things that have been sort of influential in the Civil Rights Movement?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Unfortunately, some of them acts of violence. You remember when Emmett Till was killed?

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:38.000
Yeah.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Tell us about your...

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
