And so it was kind of fun and dangerous too, but you know,

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:24.000
we, whatever we planned to do, we decided to do,

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:26.000
we going and do it.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.000
And so then they found them, and then we finally called it all

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
after, you know, we kind of got what we were expecting

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:38.000
and asked for, and so then we called it all for that mall.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:42.000
So with a, you got out of jail and you went right back on the street?

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.000
Right back on the street.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
The word intimidated at all, but.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:47.000
No, no.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
Thinking you'd probably get arrested again.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
I didn't, we didn't care then.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:54.000
Yeah, well, you arrested any other times?

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.000
No, that's on time that I was arrested.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.000
How were you treated in jail?

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:01.000
Well, nobody ever come around.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.000
Most of all of them, you know, all of them in the same city

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.000
I was close to jail.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:10.000
But we were nobody, we were about getting in or getting out.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:13.000
And you were in there for how long?

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:16.000
May were two or three hours.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:18.000
It was real, I don't know exactly.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:19.000
Yeah.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:21.000
It was scary.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
You know, it had scary.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.000
I've been arrested in a couple of times.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:27.000
Oh yeah.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
Oh, you don't know what's going to happen to you.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:38.000
But I said, you know the folk was together back in the 60s, 64 on the own up and up.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:44.000
And I said, no, so I never seen that many people on that square on all my life.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:46.000
It was that night.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:51.000
I mean, you couldn't even walk around that square.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
The streets were full.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:58.000
And the road all around that square.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:06.000
I like to talk a little bit about the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:13.000
But were you involved at the beginning in the early 1964 when the party was formed?

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:23.000
Tell us about what you were doing in Holmes County because you were getting ready to challenge the all white segregationist Democratic delegation

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:26.000
at the National (Democratic) Convention in Atlantic City.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:27.000
How did you go about that?

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:44.000
Well, when the first started out, the Freedom Democratic Party, they were when they elected President, you know, for the first president that they elected, you know, he would have like two years.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:48.000
And I think it was three here on me.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:52.000
And so when they, time was up, then they elected me.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:55.000
That's what I teed about some other time.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:36:03.000
I said, now when I was elected to be in the chair of the Freedom Democratic Party, I said, it was just only two years.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:10.000
And I said, now since I got to be chairing, and this going on for the summer year, and I said, you still ain't.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:13.000
Oh, really? You're still active in the party?

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:14.000
I'm still not.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:15.000
I'm asking you about that later.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.000
I'm still the president of the Freedom Democratic Party.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
Wow.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:33.000
And after I elected President of the Freedom Democratic Party, then I was, they also elected me as being the co-author, and I had to go to all these, 17 and 18 different communities, you know, to set up a meeting.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:40.000
And so I was the co-author, and they didn't have the chair for that day on up to the day.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:55.000
Tell us a little bit more about the early days of getting ready and choosing the delegation that would go to Atlantic City, the precinct meetings that were held to elect this group.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:37:04.000
Yeah, but I said, we were, at that time, we were all the commutes and most of meeting, you know, had different nights.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:13.000
And we were always with me on Wednesday night, and I had a different night, all the pig and red and mys and all of them.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:18.000
But we were all, and they were 30, and we would have our kind of wide meeting.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:22.000
And that's where everybody in the kind of would come to this meeting.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:33.000
And that's where we picked out the people, you know, to go to these different communities, not the county-wide meeting they were 30, and so we see a meeting every 30, and that's wonderful.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:36.000
Let's vote.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:37.000
Yeah.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:40.000
Okay, we're going.

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:44.000
Well, the Freedom Democrats lost their challenge in Atlantic City.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:45.000
Right.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:38:02.000
But then they decided to challenge the seating of the congressional delegation in that would be in January of 1965, saying that that delegation was illegal because blacks could not vote in the elections that are in the election.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:17.000
Were you active in that movement to get Fannie Lou Hamer and Annie Devine and Mrs. (Victoria) Gray seated in Washington?

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
Yeah, we were involved in all of that.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:31.000
And I said, we'd always, when something like that happened, we, you know, that there is something we would always meet, you know, because I said the kind of would be real together.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:49.000
And in a way, you meet, you know, you have a crowd, but at that time, we didn't have a center like we had now, you know, so we just needed this church, maybe like this 30, 30, 30, 30, 30, another community might have to have.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:59.000
But that's the way we, you know, and we'll pick out our delegates, you know, who are we going to send and be the delegates from the Freedom Democratic party like that?

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:04.000
In Holmes County, were the ministers active in the movement or just a couple of them?

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:21.000
We had just a couple of ministers and a couple, I'm going to say, moving the couple, it was maybe like five or six minutes, maybe five or six or seven teachers involved in, you know, when it was real active, but not.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:30.000
Why, why was that early on that the professionals were not active in the movement? You were, you were an exception.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:50.000
Well, at that time, the preacher was a free ed and the teacher was a free ed too. And so we just couldn't, we would talk to him all the time, but we just couldn't never give him to find out why they were, well we know why they weren't coming.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:40:07.000
I said a whole lot of people back then, then we were just really free ed. And then after some of them, you know, find out what was going on in the two, you know, ease on him, but the teachers and the preacher were really scared on the street.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:12.000
I can see the teachers were afraid of losing their job, right? Because they had white superintendents.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:19.000
What were the preachers afraid of? That's what I was really asking them, because they were, they were passing the black congregation.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:37.000
But I guess they might have been, you know, considering, you know, maybe buying money from the banks or something like that, but they were just, and then some of them, you know, they were telling, well you, you, you know, better than the poor, that mess and all that kind of, and some of them except like that.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:46.000
I know in some counties there were some ministers who were really working with the white people, the white people were sort of giving small favors.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:49.000
Yeah, we had a little bit of that going on too.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:52.000
You had those that you were, you could say you couldn't trust them.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Yeah, right.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:41:00.000
That they would, something would happen, somebody would be a conversation and all of a sudden it would get back to the white folks.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:17.000
And I, you know, you don't know teaching, some of them stated that right now they didn't come to the meme because I just don't spend as 12 and rate, you know, and wasn't nothing I could tell them until, and then later on one of the teachers got fired.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:23.000
And so that was not here. We, I'm selling high school and they sent for me to come down there.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:28.000
I said, when were they sent for me to come down there? And they already said that I was not, and I could tell them.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:32.000
And so when I went down there, it was nothing there but teachers.

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:38.000
And I told them I said, well, now, I said, I'm surprised y'all had me to come down here.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:44.000
I said, y'all, I heard the y'all said that I just don't spend as 12, rain, when I could tear y'all.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:50.000
I said, let me tell you one thing. I said, now you're right, I said, I can't teach school.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.000
I said, you can't read a blueprint.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:42:01.000
And I said, I said, what I got, they don't teach that in college.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:08.000
I said, that had to come from the man above, the guy that could and not have been afraid to speak out.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:16.000
And I said, but I tell you what I said before the sun goes around, I said, the teacher never fight.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.000
I'm going to be back in his position.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:24.000
And so they know on that end and they come back and told me he had a job back.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:31.000
And then that's when I told him, I said, now let you know that when you together, you can get playing dumb, but when you divide.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:41.000
And I said, that's what they was trying to do, keep the teachers and the preachers from the black wife, what we call them, men.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:44.000
So the teachers were fired and they got their jobs back.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:45.000
Yeah.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:46.000
And you were helpful in that.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:49.000
We went, we went, we went, how did you go about doing that?

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:55.000
We just called the superintendent and told me, you're going to put him back or you're going to put the boycott on.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.000
And that's all it took.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
Yeah, you must have had some power.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:00.000
We had power.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:01.000
Yeah.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:02.000
Yeah.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:03.000
Yeah.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:17.000
In her wonderful new book on the Holmes County Movement, Thunder of Freedom: Black Leadership and the Transformation of 1960s Mississippi: Black Activism in Holmes County, Mississippi, Sue Lorenzi Sojourner writes that you were, quote, unquestionably the Durant Movement leader.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:26.000
And that you spent, quote, several dangerous years opening up the predominantly White Holmes Hill Towns of Durant, West, and Goodman.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:37.000
First of all, tell us something about Sue and Henry Lorenzi, the white volunteers who came to Holmes County and the Fall of 64 and stayed for a while.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:41.000
Well, they're, Sue and Henry were here in least five years.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:48.000
And they were real active and anything that we were, you know, trying to do, they were writing that word.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:52.000
Well, they were, they were, they worked the whole five years.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:57.000
They were here, you know, if anybody, and everybody's seen the love of them.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:01.000
And, and, and we just all worked in that a year.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
A lot of this was Sue and Henry, at first.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:11.000
We were living in the, in the community center and a lot of activity after that around that.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:16.000
This, the community center, well, tell us how it got built and, and what it's important.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:20.000
It was for you and your, and the community in organizing.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:29.000
Well, and the son, I mean, you know, he was kind of a community thing, you know, different wanted volunteers, you know, and then help get it built out in my eyes.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:34.000
Yeah. And so that's, that's where it, it, it got built.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:38.000
And then, what did I say when we first started, you know, we didn't, we didn't have that.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:42.000
But about Sue and Henley, me and him kind of spearheaded everything.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:47.000
And that's where that center got built, you know, just volunteer.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:53.000
And one of the things that was coming out of that was a health clinic.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:57.000
That was started in the fall of 1964.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:01.000
A diversion here. Tell us a little bit about healthcare in the state.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:07.000
When you, when you got sick, when you were growing up, what was available to you?

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:14.000
Do you go to doctors, the hospital, what, what kind of services were there in the county?

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:20.000
One of the, serving in the kind of, back in the name was real, pofor black folk.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:30.000
I mean, cause, you know, someone didn't go to a hospital or doctor, his name was Dr. Brock and he used to go around, you know.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:35.000
Two different people's home, you know, if they would get sick or something like that,

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:41.000
cause black didn't go to a hospital too much, cause they don't have no money or something like that.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:48.000
And no clinic, but now, he, doctor, they were, you know, someone, you know, couldn't even get the people out.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:52.000
But they don't have no cars and, they don't have no good roads and things.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:56.000
And they had to walk there and they were, he was real bad back there in the day.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:59.000
I believe there weren't any black doctors in the county.

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:00.000
No, no black doctors.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:01.000
Are there now?

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.000
Yes, black doctors in the county.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:07.000
So you were dependent on white doctors?

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:08.000
White doctors.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:13.000
Did you go to their offices where they're segregated waiting rooms and things?

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:14.000
Do you remember?

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:15.000
Yeah, I remember all of that.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:21.000
I never go, but I remember, you know, that they had, you know, rooms with a white room with a black.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:26.000
Never, never, like, train station, you know,

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:33.000
bus and, you know, police.

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:42.000
And when somebody got sick later on while you had, first of all, the health clinic with the nurses who were there,

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:50.000
and then the doctor who came up from Jackson, but then you had the community health centers.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
And you have them here and now, right?

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:53.000
Yeah, right.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:56.000
Are they effective in helping people?

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:57.000
Yeah, they're really effective.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.000
Now we've got my son.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:06.000
I mean, a married clinic, you know, they got a clinic in Lexington.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:09.000
And they don't be a one here in New Rent.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:13.000
They got a big clinic up here on Toyota going to Lexington.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:18.000
And it helps a whole lot of black and one in Lexington.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:21.000
So they're real cool, I believe.

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:22.000
Yeah, they're just...

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:26.000
So we don't have no problem about it, you know, people getting sick of it here.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:33.000
And all about there, that's part of the comprehensive community health center movement across the country.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:40.000
And nearly 40 million needy people are getting help from these non-clinics centers.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:42.000
And it all started here in my...

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:43.000
Yes, right.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:44.000
That was started in my...

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:45.000
It's a health clinic.

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:49.000
It's quite an accomplishment for all of you.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:54.000
Okay, we're going to talk about political organizing.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:48:05.000
How did you go about the job of organizing, of getting people together and developing what became some power for you?

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:12.000
Well, as I say here, when I started in New Rent,

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:17.000
when the school of...

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.000
what is called the city school, New Rent High School.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:24.000
Now, it was segregated, you know, when no blacks up there.

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:27.000
And Mayor Levin thought you might have heard of him.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.000
He was still right, lawyer.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:30.000
Yeah, I knew me, yeah.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.000
Yeah, home was county.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:36.000
And so he got involved with us up here at the school.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:44.000
And so we had a meeting one night and we had, you know, been talking about the school.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.000
And so he...

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:47.000
We pointed him.

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:50.000
He was a 24-year-old school up there.

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:54.000
And then he came back and told him, you know, that we need to point...

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:57.000
To let two blacks, you know, they...

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:00.000
They didn't want two blacks to be on the board up there.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:03.000
Because he always wants you to be the odd number.

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
And so they...

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:09.000
They pointed me and Mr. D. F. One, so we just...

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:15.000
The school was a 42-black that served up there on that board.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:20.000
And so then we got from there, but at that time,

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
it's both been...

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:25.000
When they had a Prumple Law,

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:29.000
Superintendent One, both been black and one, both been white.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:34.000
So everyone owned that away for a while, but right now,

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:39.000
the Prumple and the Superintendent is right right now.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:42.000
But that's where we're all going to have to...

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:48.000
And so we tried to get them to merge with the county.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:50.000
But they figured if they...

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:53.000
Yeah, that they were going to control.

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
And so they fought that.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:58.000
And so they wouldn't communicate...

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:01.000
Or couldn't connect with the county school.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:04.000
They wanted to stay up back on their...

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:07.000
You know, they were going to be in power.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
And they were...

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:12.000
They were...

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:14.000
They were...

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
They were...

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:19.000
They were...

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:22.000
They were...

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:24.000
They were...

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.000
They fought that.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:28.000
And so then they were finally...

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.000
They made a separate school.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.000
They were...

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:34.000
They were finally...

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:36.000
They figured they'd do that.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:38.000
They wanted to lose control of it.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.000
They didn't know they were...

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.000
They wanted to lose control of it anyway.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.000
So after God liked that,

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:47.000
then a whole lot of white people moved out of...

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:48.000
Out of...

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:50.000
Out of Durant.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
And so right now,

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
God how this would say on him,

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:57.000
but that was the first thing, you know.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
And then after that,

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:00.000
then we...

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:02.000
We almost raised this risk cap.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:05.000
I mean, couldn't go on ever white, you know.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:06.000
And you...

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:07.000
You go in the back, you know,

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
and they were so afraid back then.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:10.000
So...

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:11.000
When did you do that?

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:14.000
And how did you go about integrating the cafe?

